'''Manubhai Pancholi''' is a [[Gujarati language]] novelist, author and educationist from Gujarat, India. He is also known by his pen name, '''Darshak'''. He participated in the [[Indian independence movement]] and held several offices after independence.

== Life ==
Manubhai Pancholi was born on 15 October 1914 at Panchashiya village in [[Rajkot district]], [[Gujarat]], India. He completed his primary education from Tithwa Lunsar. He left study to participate in [[Salt Satyagraha]] in 1930 when he was studying at [[Wankaner]]. He was jailed in Sabarmati, Nasik and Visapur.<ref name =lb>{{cite web|url=http://www.lokbharti.org/founder1.asp|work=Lokbharti|title=Manubhai Pancholi|accessdate =1 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=gsp>{{cite web|url=http://www.gujaratisahityaparishad.com/prakashan/photo-gallery/sahitya-sarjako/Manubhai-Pancholi.html|title=Manubhai Pancholi "Darshak"|work =[[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]]|language =Gujarati|accessdate =1 May 2014}}</ref> He started his career as a rector in educational institute, [[Dakshinamurti]] at Bhavnagar in 1932 and later joined as a professor in Gramdakshinamurt, Ambala in 1938. He was also arrested during [[Quit India Movement]] in 1942 was jailed at [[Bhavnagar]]. He served as education minister of [[Bhavnagar State]] in 1948. He co-founded Lokbharti Gramvidyapith institute with [[Nanabhai Bhatt (Lokbharti)|Nanabhai Bhatt]] in 1953 at Sanosara.<ref name =lb/><ref name=gsp/> He married Vijayaben Patel, a daughter of [[Patidar]] family from Varad village of [[Bardoli]].<ref name="ReadGujarati.com 2010">{{cite web | title=ગૂર્જર ગૌરવ – ટીના દોશી | website=ReadGujarati.com | date=4 June 2010 | url=http://archive.readgujarati.in/sahitya2/2010/06/04/gurjar-gaurav/ | language=gu | accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref> Vijayaben died on 25 April 1995.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=શ્રીમતી વિજયાબહેન પંચોળીનું દુઃખદ અવસાન|trans-title=Death note of Vijayaben Pancholi|magazine=[[Shabdasrishti]]|date=May 1995|page=18|issn=2319-3220}}</ref>

He was a member of [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]] from 1967 to 1971 and served as an education minister in 1970. He was arrested during [[The Emergency (India)|the emergency]] in 1975. He served as the president of [[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]] from 1981 to 1983.<ref name =lb/><ref name=gsp/> He also served as the chairman of the [[Gujarat Sahitya Akademi]] from 1991 to 1998.

He died on 29 August 2001 at [[Sanosara]], Bhavnagar, Gujarat following kidney ailment.<ref name =lb/><ref name=gsp/><ref name=tr>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010831/nation.htm|title =Gujarati novelist Manubhai dead|date=31 August 2001|work=The Tribune|agency =PTI}}</ref>

== Works ==
{{expand section|date=April 2016}}
His contribution to Gujarati literature is noteworthy . His two novels ''Zer To Pidha Chhe Jani Jani'' and ''Socrates'' are regarded as classic. ''Dipnirvan'' is a historical novel about the revolt against [[Magadh]] in ancient India.<ref name="Das1991">{{cite book|author=Sisir Kumar Das|title=History of Indian Literature: 1911-1956, struggle for freedom : triumph and tragedy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sqBjpV9OzcsC&pg=PA756|accessdate=4 March 2017|year=1991|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-7201-798-9|page=756}}</ref>

His classic adapted in the Gujarati film, ''Zer To Pidhan Jani Jani'' (1972) directed by [[Upendra Trivedi]].<ref name="Times 2015">{{cite web | title=Gujarati film actor Upendra Trivedi dies | website=The Times of India | date=2015-01-05 | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Gujarati-film-actor-Upendra-Trivedi-dies/articleshow/45754295.cms | accessdate=2017-03-26}}</ref> His novel ''Socrates'' was translated into [[Hindi]] by Sushila Joshi as ''Sukrat'' in 1987.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Manubhai Pancholi|author2=Sushila Joshi|title=Sukarat|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lKkGAQAAIAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Gujarat Sahitya Akademi|location=Gandhinagar}}</ref>

== Awards ==
He received [[Ranjitram Suvarna Chandrak]] in 1964, [[Sahitya Akademi Award to Gujarati Writers]] for ''Socrates'' in 1975 and [[Bharatiya Jnanpith]] [[Moortidevi Award]] for ''Zer To Pidha Chhe Jani Jani'' in 1987.<ref name =lb/><ref name=gsp/><ref name=tr/> He was awarded [[Padma Bhushan]] in 1991<ref name="Padma Awards">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 |df= }}</ref> for his work in public affairs. He also received [[Saraswati Samman]] in 1997 for his book ''Kurukshetra'' and [[Jamnalal Bajaj Award]] in 1996.<ref name="SS-2005">{{Cite news|title=Saraswati Samman for Prof Paniker|date=19 February 2006|newspaper=The Tribune|location=Chandigarh, India|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060220/cth1.htm#21|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061216215051/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060220/cth1.htm#21|archivedate=16 December 2006|deadurl=no}}</ref>

